03735nam a22006735i 9780271031767DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212001pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710317677 a10.1515/97802710317672doi  a(DE-B1597)584173  a(OCoLC)1253314171  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0120002bisacsh04a323.44/2090322221 aMurphy, Andrew R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConscience and Community :bRevisiting Toleration and Religious Dissent in Early Modern England and America /cAndrew R. Murphy. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligious toleration appears near the top of any short list of core liberal democratic values. Theorists from John Locke to John Rawls emphasize important interconnections between the principles of toleration, constitutional government, and the rule of law. Conscience and Community revisits the historical emergence of religious liberty in the Anglo-American tradition, looking deeper than the traditional emergence of toleration to find not a series of self-evident or logically connected expansions but instead a far more complex evolution. Murphy argues that contemporary liberal theorists have misunderstood and misconstrued the actual historical development of toleration in theory and practice. Murphy approaches the concept through three ";myths"; about religious toleration: that it was opposed only by ignorant, narrow-minded persecutors; that it was achieved by skeptical Enlightenment rationalists; and that tolerationist arguments generalize easily from religion to issues such as gender, race, ethnicity, and sexuality, providing a basis for identity politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn